03429nam a22004575i 9780804763257DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222007cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047632577 a10.1515/97808047632572doi  a(DE-B1597)582179  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aBUS0000002bisacsh1 aBerri, David J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Wages of Wins :bTaking Measure of the Many Myths in Modern Sport. Updated Edition /cDavid J. Berri, Martin B. Schmidt, Stacey L. Brook. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures and Tables -- tPreface -- tPreface to the Paperback Edition -- tChapter 1. Games with Numbers -- tChapter 2. Much Talking, Little Walking -- tChapter 3. Can You Buy the Fan’s Love? -- tChapter 4. Baseball’s Competitive Balance Problem? -- tChapter 5. The NBA’s Competitive Balance Problem? -- tChapter 6. Shaq and Kobe -- tChapter 7. Who Is the Best? -- tChapter 8. A Few Chicago Stories -- tChapter 9. How Are Quarterbacks Like Mutual Funds? -- tChapter 10. Scoring to Score -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aArguing about sports is as old as the games people play. Over the years sports debates have become muddled by many myths that do not match the numbers generated by those playing the games. In The Wages of Wins, the authors use layman's language and easy to follow examples based on their own academic research to debunk many of the most commonly held beliefs about sports. In this updated version of their book, these authors explain why Allen Iverson leaving Philadelphia made the 76ers a better team, why the Yankees find it so hard to repeat their success from the late 1990s, and why even great quarterbacks like Brett Favre are consistently inconsistent. The book names names, and makes it abundantly clear that much of the decision making of coaches and general managers does not hold up to an analysis of the numbers. Whether you are a fantasy league fanatic or a casual weekend fan, much of what you believe about sports will change after reading this book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aEconomics -- Sports Economics. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh1 aBrook, Stacey L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSchmidt, Martin B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476325740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804763257423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804763257/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles